  title: A Royal Edict on Encouraging Agriculture
  author: Ha Wee-ji
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I hold this truth: a nation rests upon its people, and the people rest upon their daily bread. Agriculture is the source of clothing and sustenance, the foundation upon which all governance must first build. For it determines the very life of our multitudes, bearing the heaviest burden under heaven. Without the sincere guidance of those who lead, how can we inspire our people to labor diligently in the fields and find the joy of living?

    In ancient times, the Divine Farmer first fashioned the plow and harrow to benefit all under heaven. The sage Shao Hao commanded the nine divine birds to oversee the agricultural works. Thus did the sages inherit the mandate of heaven and establish the destiny of countless generations. Emperor Yao charged the keepers of time to honor the seasons and share them with the people. Emperor Shun consulted with the Twelve Marshals, saying: "Food depends above all on not missing the season." The founders of the Xia devoted their strength to irrigation. The Shang understood the dependence of the common folk. When the Zhou arose, they built their nation upon agriculture. The poems of Bin and the writings on Idleness speak only of the hardship of tending the fields—thus was peace and stability secured. How glorious this was!

    Emperor Wen of Han issued decrees year upon year, urging the planting of trees and the tilling of soil. He reduced taxation upon farmers, bringing prosperity throughout the land. Emperor Gaozu of Tang ordered his administrators to govern with simplicity and quiet, ensuring the seasons were not lost. Emperor Taizong often told his ministers: "To provide for clothing and food, one must never lose the season." Thus was achieved the miracle of rice at three coins per measure. The Song established offices to encourage agriculture, rewarding and punishing at year's end. They sent magistrates each spring with wine to meet the elders in the fields, urging them to exhaust themselves in tilling the soil.

    Our great founder received the mandate of heaven and first reformed the land system, rescuing the people from ruin and granting them the benefits of farming. His regulations for encouragement and reward are recorded in our laws. The second emperor continued his work, further advancing the labors of sowing and harvest. Fearing that simple folk might be ignorant of cultivation, he commanded learned officials to translate agricultural texts into our own language and distribute them widely, that wisdom might reach posterity.

    I, though unworthy, have inherited this legacy. Day and night I toil in reverence and care, looking always to the precedents of old and the example of my ancestors. Since agricultural matters concern those officials closest to the people, I have carefully selected and personally exhorted them. I have sent forth investigators to test methods proven in each region, gathering these into a comprehensive work—the Direct Explanation of Agricultural Affairs—that common farmers might easily understand. For all practices that benefit the harvest, I have sought to investigate and implement thoroughly. My aim is that every person exhaust their strength and no land lie barren.

    Yet still, when harvests fail even once, hunger appears in our people's faces. This troubles me greatly, for it means my officials have not fully embraced these teachings.

    I have observed the virtuous magistrates of old. Those who brought prosperity to their regions, winning genuine benefit for the people, all succeeded through diligence and compassion. Gong Sui, appointed to Bohai, worked to encourage farming and sericulture. When common folk carried swords, he urged them to trade these weapons for oxen. In spring he encouraged them to the fields; in winter he evaluated their harvest. The people prospered. Zhao Xin Shen, appointed to Nanyang, delighted in bringing benefit to his people. He personally encouraged farming, walking constantly through the fields and waterways, investigating springs and opening ditches to expand irrigation. The people gained its benefits and all labored in the fields.

    Ren Yan, appointed to Jiuzhen, found a land where hunting was the custom and ox-plowing unknown. He had farming tools cast, taught the people to clear the land, and year by year more soil was opened. The people became satisfied. Xin Zan, appointed to Henei, urged both farming and sericulture with personal inspections, rewarding the diligent with silk and punishing the lazy. Zhu Xi, when appointed to Nankang, published notices encouraging the people, detailing every step from plowing and manuring to weeding, planting hemp and beans, and repairing reservoirs. He explained these matters patiently and personally toured the fields, teaching rather than merely punishing.

    Why did these wise ones labor so? Because the nature of common folk is this: if led, they strive; if abandoned to themselves, they grow lazy. An ancient sage said: "Even a single humble scholar, if he truly loves all things, shall bring benefit to mankind." How much more, then, should those who hold the power of magistrate or commissioner—who hold the means to bring about prosperity or ruin, whose own person determines the welfare of an entire region—not be able to surpass the ancients if their hearts are sincere in caring for the people?

    In farming, early effort brings early harvest; much labor brings much yield. Thus the essence of agricultural governance lies solely in this: do not let the seasons pass, do not rob the people of their strength. Each grain has its season; miss it once, and you cannot recover it in that year. One person cannot divide their strength; if officials requisition it, how can we demand they work the fields? Yet if humans do their part, even an unfavorable heaven can be overcome. Such was the field division of Yi Yin and the rotating fields of Zhao Guo.

    From recent experience: in the year Ding-si, when we cultivated fields in the royal garden with full human effort, though drought came, it brought no disaster—the rice grew abundantly. This shows clearly that even heaven's calamities may be overcome by human labor.

    The traditions say: "The people's life depends on diligence; with diligence, there is no shortage." The Classics say: "The lazy farmer seeks only ease, refusing to labor earnestly. Without service to the fields, there will be no millet at harvest." Thus we learn: excess of labor is preferable to idleness.

    Yet though the people wish to labor, if we do not direct them in season, their strength cannot be employed. We call the seventh lunar month "Grain-in-Ear" because human strength is limited and not all can plant early. Yet if they plant by this time, there remains hope for autumn harvest. We fix this deadline not to demand all plant then, but to show that timely planting surpasses untimely loss. Agricultural texts themselves say: "Generally, earliness is better."

    But our magistrates, bound by old habits, let the season pass while still saying "it is not yet time." They do not promptly settle disputes over fields. They do not urgently distribute seed grain or provide sustenance for the hungry. And even when they act with urgency—reporting to the provincial overseer, who reports to the ministry, which submits a memorial—by the time these reports circulate, the proper season has passed. Some, not knowing the right time for planting, rush people to sow too early, and the sprouts die. Some, truly ignorant of the calendar, plan poorly and miss the moment entirely. Is this the way to share in governance and show love for the people?

    Let all who share in ruling with me understand this charge: embrace the trust I place in you, follow our ancestors' generous treatment of the people, observe the precedents of former wise rulers. Inquire widely about what suits each region's nature; consult what the agricultural texts teach. Plan ahead—neither too early nor too late. Above all, do not demand other duties that would steal the farming season. Each of you must give your full heart. Guide the people toward their foundation. Have them serve the fields with all their strength. Let them honor their parents and raise their families. Thus shall we preserve our people's lives and strengthen our nation's root. When every home has enough and every person has plenty, the customs of propriety and yielding will flourish. When seasons are temperate and harvests abundant, all shall share in peace and prosperity. Let the Ministry of Revenue heed my deepest wish and proclaim these principles throughout the realm.
